{%- liquid
  assign current_variant = product.selected_or_first_available_variant
%}

<div data-section-id="{{ section.id }}" data-section-type="product">
  {%- comment -%}
    Layout max-width cap. Figma designs the PDP at 1440px wide; without a
    constraint the `lg:w-1/2` columns stretch to fill wide monitors
    (3000px+ on HiDPI displays), pushing the gallery to absurd sizes and
    leaving huge gutters around the info column. `max-w-[1440px] mx-auto`
    caps the layout at the design width and centers it on wider viewports.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  <div class="max-w-[1440px] mx-auto flex flex-col lg:flex-row">
    <div class="lg:w-1/2 lg:shrink-0">
      {% render 'product-detail-gallery',
                 product: product,
                 current_variant: current_variant
      %}
    </div>

    <div class="lg:w-1/2 lg:flex lg:justify-center">
      {% render 'product-detail-form',
                 product: product,
                 current_variant: current_variant,
                 current_collection: collection
      %}
    </div>
  </div>

  {%- comment -%}
    "You may also like" — async-fetched via the Section Rendering API.
    Initial render is an empty placeholder; the productRecommendations TS
    component fetches `sections/product-recommendations.liquid` with the
    current product id + `limit=12` + `intent=related`, and swaps the
    response into this element on mount. See
    `_scripts/components/productRecommendations.ts`.

    `limit=12` chosen to fill a 4-column desktop grid three rows deep
    (12 cards total) with plenty of horizontal-scroll content on mobile.
    Also sits comfortably above the `recommendations.products_count > 4`
    threshold in `product-recommendations.liquid` that gates the scroll
    arrows — without enough cards to scroll, the arrows would render
    but do nothing.

    `overflow-x: clip` on this wrapper keeps the rail's internal overflow
    (12 cards wider than the viewport) from contributing to
    `document.scrollWidth`. Without this, browsers report a
    `documentElement.scrollWidth` larger than the viewport even though
    body's `overflow-x: clip` prevents actual page scrolling — creates
    rubber-band / wide-page visual artifacts on some browsers.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  <div
    data-component="product-recommendations"
    data-url="{{ routes.product_recommendations_url }}?section_id=product-recommendations&product_id={{ product.id }}&limit=12&intent=related"
    class="overflow-x-clip"
  ></div>

  <script type="application/ld+json">
    {{ product | structured_data }}
  </script>
</div>

{% schema %}
{
  "name": "Product - Main",
  "settings": [

  ]
}
{% endschema %}
